<br>
My portfolio: <br>
<br>
Avalon Hill's Squad Leader <br>
<br>
Avalon Hill's Rise and Decline of the Third Reich<br>
(wargame with an 80-page rule book)<br>
<br>
Risk (the mother of all beer and pretzels 1980s wargames) <br>
<br>
Diplomacy (this is a classic.Richard Nixon played this, so did Henry Kissinger, so did Jean Kirkpatrick) <br>
<br>
World in Flames (by Aussie Design Group). A copycat of Avalon Hill's Third Reich, except that this game covered the entire globe, not just the European Theatre.<br>
<br>
Empires in Arms.  <br>
The MOTHER of all Napoleonic Grand Strategy games of the 1990s. I loved playing the Empire of Austria-Hungary. And repeatedly saw my butt kicked over and over by competent French player. <br>
<br>
Victory in the Pacific.  Another Avalon Hill classic that won numerous game awards for years. <br>
<br>
Fortress America &amp; Axis and Allies <br>
(Milton Bradley cheesey poof wargames) <br>
<br>
Star Fleet Battles (tactical and SciFi) <br>
<br>
FASA's BattleTech (also tactical and SciFi)<br>
<br>
If you havent played at least ONE of the games I listed above.... you can never call yourself a true wargamer grognard.  Ever. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
My current favorite PC-based wargame?? <br>
Europa Universalis II <br>
http://www.paradoxplaza.com/eu2.asp<br>
<br>
Westfallen looks pretty nice... but unfortunately I dont have the patience for slow PBEM player-turn-for-turn games any more. Way too slow for me.  :/<br>
<br>
