<br>
Everything I listed above were published board games, with the exception of Europa Universalis II, which is strictly a PC-based game which was based loosely on Avalon Hill's two Napoleonic Era games.... War and Peace AND Empires in Arms. <br>
<br>
You're missing out bigtime if you havent even touched Europa Universalis II.  I mean, Paradox (the devs) only got 5 or 6 major PC Strategy Games awards for that game alone.  But then again, if you're not a big fan of the historical era from 1419-1820, then you arent missing much.  Basically it covers the era of European exploration, exploitation, domination, empire building, and colonialism..... from around Columbus to the end of Napoleon. <br>
<br>
EU2 is probably the ONLY historical wargame on the market today that covers detailed political historical features tactics such as &quot;ethnic cleansing&quot;, forced religious conversions, the Protestant-Catholic wars of religion, slave trade in Africa, etc.  It's accurate as it will ever get. Heck I play as the Ottoman Empire, I invade and take the southern Austrian-Hungarian provinces.... and then forcefully convert them from Catholic to Sunni Muslim. Such fun! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
EUII has the option to play real-time.... but it's really more &quot;pause-based&quot; time.  You have a time controller that speeds up, slows down, or pauses the game time flow. <br>
<br>
Star Fleet Battles.... ahhh give me back my Romulan Condor dreadnoughts and my fleets of SparrowHawk light cruisers, and FireHawk cruisers!  <br>
<br>
